programming_language.simple-data-types:
In programming, data type refers to the type of value a variable 
            as and what type of mathematical, relational or logical operations can be applied 
            without causing an error.



            A data type is an attribute associated with a piece of 
            data (variable) that tells a computer system how to interpret its value.



            Data-types in Programming:



            short int - has value range [-32,768 to 32,767] - format specifier %hd - 
            occupies 2 bytes memory;



            unsigned short int - has value range [-32,768 to 65,535] - format specifier %hu - 
            occupies 2 bytes memory;



            unsigned int - has value range [0 to 4,294,967,295] - format specifier %u - 
            occupies 4 bytes memory;



            int - has value range [-2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647] - format specifier %d - 
            occupies 4 bytes memory;



            long int - has value range [-2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647] - 
            format specifier %ld - occupies 4 bytes memory;



            unsigned long int - has value range [0 to 4,294,967,295 ] - format specifier %lu -
            occupies 4 bytes memory;



            long long int - has value range [-(2^63) to (2^63)-1] - format specifier %lld - 
            occupies 8 bytes memory;



            unsigned long long int - has value range [-(2^63) to 18,446,744,073,709,551,615 ] - 
            format specifier %llu  - occupies 8 bytes memory;



            signed char - has value range [-128 to 127] - format specifier %c - occupies 
            1 byte memory;



            unsigned char - has value range [0 to 255] - format specifier %c - occupies 
            1 byte memory;



            float - has value range [1.2E-38 to 3.4E+38] - format specifier %f - occupies 
            4 bytes memory;



            double - has value range [1.7E-308 to 1.7E+308] - format specifier %lf - 
            occupies 8 bytes memory;



            long double - has value range [3.4E-4932 to 1.1E+4932] - format specifier %Lf  - 
            occupies 16 bytes memory;

programming_language.ternary-operator:
Ternary operator is used for decision making instead of placing longer if and else
            conditional statements.



            Syntax:
            condition ? value_if_true : value_if_false


            The statement evaluates to value_if_true if condition is met, and value_if_false 
            otherwise.



            The ternary operator take three arguments:




            The first is a comparison argument;

            The second is the result upon a true comparison;

            The third is the result upon a false comparison;

programming_language.generic-programming:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*



            In C Language generic programming can be achieved using:





            Variable argument lists;

            Using void * and function pointers to write generic code;

            Using libraries to reuse code without copying and recompiling;

            Using plugins to get run-time overriding;

            Using macros;


0   

1   //Example of generic programming in C using function-like macros:

2   

3   #include <stdio.h>

4   

5   #define incr(x) (++(*x))

6   

7   int main()

8   {

9   

10      int i=5;

11      float f=5.6f;

12      char c='a';

13  

14      incr(&i);

15      incr(&f);

16      incr(&c);

17  

18      printf("i=%d; f=%f; c=%c\n", i,f,c);

19  

20      return 0;

21  }

