programming_language.interfaces:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*
An interface in C# is mostly like a class but with some differences:
1. An interface cannot have field members/variable members (can have only functions/methods, delegates, events or proprieties).
2. An interface cannot contain implementations for the functions/methods (an implementation of a function/method is the code between the brackets).
3. An interface has public fields set by default, so inside an interface you cannot use the public acces-modifier for its members.
4. A class can inherit from an interface. But with the condition of providing the implementation for all the interface function/method members.
5. When a class provides implementation of an interface function member, it also needs to make the member function public. (The public access modifier must be used.)
6. A class or struct can inherit from MORE interfaces at the same time. Whereas a class or struct cannot inherit from more then one class.
7. An interface cannot be instanciated (an instance, object of the interface cannot be created), because doing this it would mean that you would be able to call a function from the interface, and the interface cannot contain implemented members.
0
1 //Example of using creating/using interfaces
2
3 using System;
4
5 namespace project30_interfaces
6 {
7 //Creating an interface:
8 public interface Ifirst_interface //an interface name usually starts with I (capital i).
9 {
10 //int age; -> an interface cannot have such fields (variable fields).
11 //public void Print(); -> an interface cannot contain public access modifier.
12
13 void Print(); //this is a function of the interface.
14 }
15 public interface Isecond_interface : Ithird_interface
16 {
17 void Print2();
18 }
19 public interface Ithird_interface
20 {
21 void Print3();
22 }
23
24 class Program
25 {
26 public static void Main(string[] args)
27 {
28 Inherited_from_interface Iobject = new Inherited_from_interface();
29 Iobject.Print();
30 Iobject.Print3(); //calling the grandpa's function.
31 Console.Write("Press any key to continue . . . ");
32 Console.ReadKey(true);
33 }
34 }
35
36 class Inherited_from_interface : Ifirst_interface, Isecond_interface
37 {
38 /* A class that inherits from an interface HAS to provide implementations for all
39 * the interface methods members.
40 */
41
42 public void Print() //providing implementation for the interface function.
43 {
44 /*
45 * IMPORTANT:
46 * when providing implementation for an interface function/method member you have
47 * to specify it to be public. (YOU need to use the public access modifier.)
48 *
49 * IF A CLASS inherits from multiple interfaces, then the class has to provide
50 * members.implementation for all the interface members.
51 *
52 * IF A CLASS inherits from an interface which inherits from another interface,
53 * then the class has to provide implementation for both the parent
54 * interface and grandparent interface as well.
55 */
56
57 Console.WriteLine("Class inherited from an interface.");
58 }
59
60 //A method can be implemented like this. (The brackets can be empty.)
61 public void Print2()
62 {
63 //By implementing a function inherited from an interface,
64 //you have to assure that the functionis public, and there
65 //exists the brackets (where the implementation should be made).
66 }
67
68 //this function is inherited from an interface which inherits from another interface.
69 public void Print3()
70 {
71 Console.WriteLine("This is the grandpa's function!");
72 }
73 }
74 }
75

