programming_language.abstraction:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*


            Abstract object constructors are those constructors that 
            cannot be instantiated. That means that no object can be 
            created out of them. 
            The purpose of using such constructors is to provide inheritance 
            to other prototypes. 



            In this way the functionality can be shared amongst the objects without 
            needing any instances.



            Blocking a constructor from being instantiated will result in error.

0   

1   //Example of abstraction

2   

3   function House ()

4   {

5       this.personName = "";

6       

7       //This will block anyone from creating an instance with this constructor.

8       throw Error ("Cannot instantiate an abstract object.");

9       

10  }

11  

12  //This is a public-static method of House object;

13  House.prototype.printMsg = function()

14  {

15      document.write("Printing a message!" + "<br>");

16  }

17  

18  function Home(pn)

19  {

20      //Using the base object (Home) field named personName;

21      personName = pn;

22      

23      this.getHomeOwnerName = function ()

24      {

25          return personName;

26      }

27  }

28  

29  //Creating the inheritance:

30  

31  //House is gonna be the base class for Home constructor

32  

33  Home.prototype = Object.create(House.prototype); 

34  

35  /*

36  Object.create - will create an object without using the constructor.

37  */

38  

39  //Creating an instance of the child object:

40  var h = new Home("Adrian");

41  

42  //Using the child object method and parent object field:

43  document.write("Owner's name: " + h.getHomeOwnerName() + "<br>");

44  document.write("Is name owned by this class: " + h.hasOwnProperty("personName") + "<br>");

45  document.write("Is h instance of House: " + (h instanceof House) + "<br>")

46  document.write("Is h instance of Home: " + (h instanceof Home) + "<br>")

47  

48  //Calling the base object method;

49  h.printMsg();

50

programming_language.generic-programming:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*


            TypeScript is a syntactic superset of JavaScript which adds static typing which
            also facilitates the use of generic-programming.



            This basically means that TypeScript adds syntax on top of JavaScript, 
            allowing developers to add data types.




            Why should I use TypeScript?




            JavaScript is a loosely typed language. It can be difficult to understand 
            what types of data are being passed around within the script.



            In JavaScript, function parameters and variables don't have 
            any information! 
            So developers need to look at documentation, or guess based on the implementation.



            TypeScript allows specifying the types of data being passed around within 
            the code, and has the ability to report errors when the types don't match.



            For example, TypeScript will report an error when passing a string into a 
            function that expects a number. JavaScript will not do that.



            TypeScript uses compile time type checking. Which means it checks if the 
            specified types match 
            before running the code, not while running the code.



            Generics allow creating 'type variables' which can be used to 
            create classes, functions and 
            type aliases that don't need to explicitly define the types that they use.



0   

1   //Example of generic programming in JavaScript using TypeScript:

2   

3   function createPair<S, T>(v1: S, v2: T): [S, T] 

4   {

5     return [v1, v2];

6   }

7   console.log(createPair<string, number>('hello', 42)); 

8   

9   //OUTPUT: ['hello', 42]

10  


0   

1   //Example of generic class implementation

2   

3   class NamedValue<T> 

4   {

5     private _value: T | undefined;

6   

7     constructor(private name: string) {}

8   

9     public setValue(value: T) 

10    {

11      this._value = value;

12    }

13  

14    public getValue(): T | undefined 

15    {

16      return this._value;

17    }

18  

19    public toString(): string 

20    {

21      return `${this.name}: ${this._value}`;

22    }

23  }

24  

25  let value = new NamedValue<number>('myNumber');

26  value.setValue(10);

27  console.log(value.toString()); // myNumber: 10

28

programming_language.variable-arguments-lists:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*

0   

1   //Example of using variable number of arguments in JavaScript:

2   

3   /*

4   The argument object is used to store the value of arguments of a function.

5   Accessing the argument object outside a function will result in undefined error.

6   The argument object is not an array, but it only has one property of the array, 

7   and that is .length

8   */

9   

10  function Myfct(a,b,c)

11  {

12      document.write("The function has: " + arguments.length + " arguments.<br>");

13      

14      //arguments.length will return the number of arguments that was passed to the function. 

15      //Not the number of parameters that the function has. 

16      

17      document.write("<br>The arguments are: <br>");

18      for (var i =0; i<arguments.length; i++)

19      {

20          document.write(" " + arguments[i] + " ");

21      }

22      document.write("<br>");

23      

24  };

25  

26  /*

27  The Myfct(a,b,c) function has 3 parameters: a,b,c 

28  but it is called below using 5 arguments: 0,1,3,4,5

29  */

30  

31  Myfct(0,1,3,4,5); 

32  

33  //In JavaScript a function can be called using any number of arguments. 

34  //The unnecessary ones will be ignored.

35  

36  //Creating a function with various number of arguments;

37  

38  function getSum() 

39  {

40      var sum=0;

41      for (var i=0; i<arguments.length; i++)

42      {

43          sum+=arguments[i];

44      }

45      return sum;

46      

47  };

48  

49  //See how the getSum() function is declared without any parameters 

50  //but it is called with various number of arguments each time.

51  

52  document.write("<br>The sum of all the arguments is: " + getSum(1,12,3,22,1,3,4,22) + "<br>");

53  document.write("The sum of all the arguments is: " + getSum(-2,10,4,21) + "<br>");

54  

55  //the function was called with different number of arguments each time and 

56  //it worked fine every time.

57

