programming_language.encapsulation:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*



            Encapsulation in Java:




            Encapsulation in Java is a mechanism of wrapping 
            the data (variables) 
            and code acting on the data (methods) 
            together as a single unit. 



            In encapsulation, the variables of a class will be 
            hidden from other classes, and can be accessed only through 
            the methods of their current classes.



            Therefore, it is also known as data hiding.



0   

1   //Example of using Encapsulation in Java

2    

3   // Person Class

4   class Person 

5   {

6       // Encapsulating the name and age

7       // only approachable and used using

8       // methods defined

9       

10      private String name;

11      private int age;

12   

13      public String getName() { return name; }

14   

15      public void setName(String name) { this.name = name; }

16   

17      public int getAge() { return age; }

18   

19      public void setAge(int age) { this.age = age; }

20  }

21   

22  public class Main 

23  {

24      public static void main(String[] args)

25      {

26          // person object created

27          Person person = new Person();

28          person.setName("John");

29          person.setAge(30);

30   

31          // Using methods to get the values from the

32          // variables

33          System.out.println("Name: " + person.getName());

34          System.out.println("Age: " + person.getAge());

35      }

36  }

