        Interface to interface inheritance:



0   

1   //FILE: Sports.java

2   public interface Sports 

3   {

4       public void setHomeTeam(String name);

5       public void setVisitingTeam(String name);

6   }

7   

8   //FILE: Football.java

9   public interface Football extends Sports 

10  {

11      public void homeTeamScored(int points);

12      public void visitingTeamScored(int points);

13      public void endOfQuarter(int quarter);

14  }

15  

16  //FILE: Hockey.java

17  public interface Hockey extends Sports 

18  {

19      public void homeGoalScored();

20      public void visitingGoalScored();

21      public void endOfPeriod(int period);

22      public void overtimePeriod(int ot);

23  }

24  


            Whatever class will implement interface Hockey will have to 
            provide implementation to all its methods + the extended methods from Sports 
            interface.


            Same goes for whatever class will implement Football.

programming_language.abstraction:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*


            Abstraction in Java:



            In Java, abstraction is achieved using abstract classes and 
            interfaces.



            A class which contains the abstract keyword in its declaration is 
            known as abstract class.



            Abstract classes may or may not contain abstract methods, 
            i.e., methods without a body.


            Example: ( public void get(); )



            But, if a class has at least one abstract method, then the class 
            must be declared abstract.



            If a class is declared abstract, it cannot be instantiated.



            To use an abstract class, you have to inherit it from another 
            class, provide implementations to the abstract methods in it.



            If you inherit an abstract class, you have to provide implementations 
            to all the abstract methods in it.

0   

1   //Example of abstraction using interfaces:

2   

3   //Defining an interface

4   interface Animal 

5   {

6       public void animalSound(); // interface method (does not have a body)

7       public void sleep(); // interface method (does not have a body)

8   }

9   

10  // Pig "implements" the Animal interface

11  class Pig implements Animal 

12  {

13      public void animalSound() 

14      {

15          // The body of animalSound() is provided here

16          System.out.println("The pig says: wee wee");

17      }

18      

19      public void sleep() 

20      {

21          // The body of sleep() is provided here

22          System.out.println("Zzz");

23      }

24  }

25  

26  class Main 

27  {

28      public static void main(String[] args) 

29      {

30          Pig myPig = new Pig();  // Create a Pig object

31          myPig.animalSound();

32          myPig.sleep();

33      }

34  }

35

programming_language.generic-programming:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*


            Generic Programming in Java:



            Generic Classes:



            In Java a generic class declaration is similar to a 
            regular non-generic class declaration, 
            except that the class name is followed by a 
            <type parameter> section.



            For all generics the <type parameter> section can 
            contain one or more <type parameters> separated by commas.



            Such generics are called parameterized types because they 
            accept one or more parameters.

0   

1   //Example of generic class declaration in Java:

2   

3   package project29;

4   

5   public class GenericClass <T> 

6   {

7      private T t;

8   

9      public void set(T t) 

10     {

11        this.t = t;

12     }

13  

14     public T get() 

15     {

16        return t;

17     }

18  }

19  

20  

        In Java each data type has an object correspondant: 


        int (primitive) -> Integer (object)

        double (primitive) -> Double (object)

        etc...



        We could use generics to wrap primitive types 
        into objects.



        Example: java.lang.Integer class  wraps a value of the 
        primitive type int into an object. 


        The object of type Integer contains a single field 
        whose type is int



        Generic Methods:



        Generic methods are methods that can be called with arguments of 
        different types.
        Based on the types of the arguments passed to the 
        generic method, the compiler handles each method 
        call appropriately.

0   

1   //Example of generic class instantiation in Java:

2   //Example of generic method/function definition in Java:

3   

4   package project29;

5   

6   import java.util.Scanner;

7    

8   public class Project29 

9   {

10      public static void main(String[] args) 

11      {

12          //Instantiating the GenericClass from previous example:

13          GenericClass <Integer> FirstGeneric_Class = new GenericClass<Integer>();

14          FirstGeneric_Class.set(2);

15          System.out.printf("Value of GenericClass object: %d\n", FirstGeneric_Class.get());

16          

17          //Creating some arrays:

18          Integer [] myArray = new Integer[] {1,42,13,24,5};

19          Character [] myCharArray = new Character[] {'D', 'N', 'C', 'A'};

20          

21          //Calling the generic method printArray() on 2 different arrays:

22          printArray(myArray);

23          printArray(myCharArray);

24          

25          //Keep the window opened until a key is pressed:

26          Scanner myscanner = new Scanner(System.in);

27          myscanner.next();

28      }

29      

30      //Creating a generic method/function:

31      public static < E > void printArray( E[] inputArray ) 

32      {

33          // Display array elements

34          for(E element : inputArray) 

35          {

36           System.out.printf("%s ", element);

37          }

38          System.out.println();

39      }

40  }

41  /*

42  Another example of using generics:

43  public final class Integer extends Number implements Comparable<Integer>

44  */

