programming_language.decorators:
*General-Programming-Knowledge*


            Decorators in Java:



            In order to implement a decorator in Java, the following steps
            needs to be followed:



            1. Component Interface:



            Defining the interface or the abstract class 
            declaring the methods that will be 
            implemented. 


            In this case Car will be the component interface.



0   

1   //the interface defining the methods 

2   //that will be implemented.

3   

4   package com.journaldev.design.decorator;

5   

6   public interface Car 

7   {

8       public void assemble();

9   }

10  


        2. Component Implementation:



        The basic implementation of the component interface. 
        We can have BasicCar class as our component implementation.



0   

1   //the basic implementation of 

2   //the Car interface

3   

4   package com.journaldev.design.decorator;

5   

6   public class BasicCar implements Car 

7   {

8       @Override

9       public void assemble() 

10      {

11          System.out.print("Basic Car.");

12      }

13  }

14  


        3. Decorator: 



        Defining the decorator class that implements the component 
        interface. 

        The component variable needs to be accessible to the child decorator classes, 
        so it should be defined as protected variable .

0   

1   //the decorator class implementing

2   //Car interface

3   

4   package com.journaldev.design.decorator;

5   

6   public class CarDecorator implements Car 

7   {

8   

9       protected Car car;

10  

11      public CarDecorator(Car c)

12      {

13          this.car=c;

14      }

15  

16      @Override

17      public void assemble() 

18      {

19          this.car.assemble();

20      }

21  

22  }

23  


        4. Concrete Decorators:



        Extending the base decorator functionality and modifying the 
        component behavior accordingly. We can have concrete decorator classes 
        as LuxuryCar and SportsCar.



0   

1   //a second decorator extending the

2   //functionality of the first decorator

3   

4   package com.journaldev.design.decorator;

5   

6   public class SportsCar extends CarDecorator 

7   {

8       public SportsCar(Car c) 

9       {

10          super(c);

11      }

12  

13      @Override

14      public void assemble()

15      {

16          super.assemble();

17          System.out.print(" Adding features of Sports Car.");

18      }

19  }

20  


0   

1   //using the decorator to modify the 

2   //component behaviour

3   

4   package com.journaldev.design.decorator;

5   

6   public class LuxuryCar extends CarDecorator 

7   {

8       public LuxuryCar(Car c) 

9       {

10          super(c);

11      }

12  

13      @Override

14      public void assemble()

15      {

16          super.assemble();

17          System.out.print(" Adding features of Luxury Car.");

18      }

19  }

